#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:1
msgid "libcore for low-level Rust"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.6](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.6-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:5
msgid ""
"Rust’s standard library is two-tiered: there’s a small core library, "
"`libcore`, and the full standard library, `libstd`, that builds on top of "
"it. `libcore` is completely platform agnostic, and requires only a handful "
"of external symbols to be defined. Rust’s `libstd` builds on top of "
"`libcore`, adding support for things like memory allocation and I/O. "
"Applications using Rust in the embedded space, as well as those writing "
"operating systems, often eschew `libstd`, using only `libcore`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/platform-and-target-support/libcore-for-low-level-rust.md:13
msgid ""
"As an additional note, while building _libraries_ with `libcore` is "
"supported today, building full applications is not yet stable."
msgstr ""

